  "prompt": "Why do electrons and protons attract each other?",
  "response": "Electrons and protons attract each other due to the **electromagnetic force**, which is one of the four fundamental forces in nature. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Opposite Charges**:  \n   Protons have a **positive electric charge**, and electrons have a **negative electric charge**. According to the laws of electromagnetism, opposite charges attract each other.\n\n2. **Coulomb's Law**:  \n   The force of attraction between an electron and a proton is described by **Coulomb's law**. This law states that the force between two charged particles is directly proportional to the product of their charges and inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them. Mathematically, it is expressed as:  \n   \\[\n   F = k_e \\frac{q_1 q_2}{r^2}  \n   \\]  \n   Here, \\(F\\) is the force, \\(k_e\\) is Coulomb's constant, \\(q_1\\) and \\(q_2\\) are the charges (proton +e and electron -e), and \\(r\\) is the distance between them.\n\n3. **Electromagnetic Interaction**:  \n   The attraction is mediated by the exchange of **virtual photons**, which are the force-carrying particles of the electromagnetic field. This interaction ensures that the electron is bound to the proton in an atom, forming a stable system.\n\n### Why Not Repel?  \nElectrons and protons attract because their charges are opposite. If two like charges (e.g., two electrons or two protons) are brought together, they would repel each other due to the same electromagnetic force.\n\nThis attraction between electrons and protons is fundamental to the structure of atoms and the stability of matter. Without it, atoms would not form, and the universe as we know it would not exist.",
